## context
Divergent control-flow paths inconsistently free the same heap object, allowing some execution paths to invoke free on it more than once.

## guideline
1. When freeing memory in conditional branches or exception-handling paths, ensure consistent deallocation logic across all branches to avoid double-freeing the same object.
2. Always track the deallocation status of dynamically allocated objects using nullification or state flags to guarantee each object is freed exactly once across all execution paths.
3. Immediately set pointers to NULL after freeing memory to prevent double-free errors across different branches.

```c
// ❌ Bad example: same object freed in different branches
void *ptr = malloc(100);
if (condition) {
    free(ptr);
} else {
    free(ptr);  // May cause double-free on different paths
}

// ✅ Good example: unified cleanup point with state tracking
void *ptr = malloc(100);
int freed = 0;
if (condition) {
    // processing logic
}
if (!freed) {
    free(ptr);
    ptr = NULL;
    freed = 1;
}
```


